# Pump Maintenance Program — Mechanical Power Transmission

## Overview
Pumps are both a controlled process element (see `pid-control-loops.md`) and
a mechanical asset requiring dedicated maintenance — specifically around
**power transmission**: how motor power is delivered to the pump (direct
coupling, belt drive) and the rotating components that can wear or fail.

## Power transmission types covered
| Type | Description | Common Failure Points |
|---|---|---|
| Direct coupling | Motor shaft directly coupled to pump shaft | Misalignment, coupling element wear, bearing wear |
| Belt drive | Motor drives pump via belt/pulley | Belt tension/wear, pulley alignment, bearing wear |
| Mechanical seal | Seals pump shaft where it exits the casing | Seal face wear, leakage, dry-running damage |

## Preventive maintenance tasks
| Task | Frequency | What to check |
|---|---|---|
| Coupling alignment check | Quarterly (or per vibration trend) | Angular/parallel misalignment within tolerance |
| Bearing inspection | Monthly | Temperature, noise/vibration, lubrication condition |
| Mechanical seal inspection | Monthly | Leakage at seal, visible wear |
| Belt tension/condition (if belt-driven) | Monthly | Tension per spec, cracking/glazing, pulley alignment |
| Lubrication | Per manufacturer schedule | Correct grease/oil type and quantity — over-lubrication is also a failure cause |
| Vibration analysis | Quarterly (or continuous if monitored) | Trend against baseline to catch bearing/alignment issues early |

## Corrective troubleshooting — common pump failure symptoms
| Symptom | Likely Cause(s) | Diagnostic Approach |
|---|---|---|
| Excessive vibration | Misalignment, bearing wear, cavitation | Check alignment first (cheapest to verify), then bearing condition, then suction conditions (cavitation) |
| Seal leakage | Seal face wear, misalignment inducing shaft deflection | Inspect seal; check alignment before replacing seal — misalignment causes repeat failures |
| Reduced flow/pressure | Impeller wear, suction blockage, worn wear rings | Check suction strainer/blockage first (simplest), then internal wear |
| Overheating (motor or bearing) | Misalignment, bearing lubrication issue, electrical overload | Cross-reference with `corrective-troubleshooting-method.md` (maintenance repo) for systematic diagnosis |

## Link to AMDEC and PM scheduling
Following the same logic as `amdec-fmea-analysis.md`
(`blueprint-reading-mechanical-install` repo), pump criticality (e.g. a
single transfer pump with no backup vs. a redundant dosing pump) should
drive PM frequency — a critical single-point-of-failure pump warrants
tighter monitoring intervals than a redundant one.

